company /ˈkʌmpənɪ/

(companies) 

1. N-COUNT-COLL/N-IN-NAMES A company is a business organization that makes money by selling goods or services. 公司 

例： Sheila found some work as a secretary in an insurance company. 希拉在一家保险公司找到了一份做秘书的工作。 

2. N-COUNT-COLL/N-IN-NAMES A company is a group of opera singers, dancers, or actors who work together. 剧团 

例： ...the Phoenix Dance Company. …凤凰舞蹈团。 

3. N-COUNT/N-IN-NAMES A company is a group of soldiers that is usually part of a battalion or regiment, and that is divided into two or more platoons. 连 

例： The division will consist of two tank companies and one infantry company. 该师将由两个坦克连和一个步兵连组成。 

4. N-UNCOUNT Company is having another person or other people with you, usually when this is pleasant or stops you feeling lonely. 陪伴 

例： 'I won't stay long.'—'No, please. I need the company.' “我不会呆很久。” — “别，请别走。我需要陪伴。” 

例： Ross had always enjoyed the company of women. 罗斯总是喜欢女人的陪伴。 

5.  →  see also joint-stock company , public company 

6. PHRASE If you have company , you have a visitor or friend with you. 有客人 

例： He didn't say he had company. 他没说他有客人。 

7. PHRASE If you keep someone company , you spend time with them and stop them from feeling lonely or bored. 陪某人做伴 

例： Why don't you stay here and keep Emma company? 你为什么不留在这儿陪埃玛做伴？

